# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillic-o-variants
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] This is a list of rare glyph variants of the Cyrillic letter O.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] They were proposed for inclusion into Unicode in 2007 and incorporated as in Unicode 5.1.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] The letter resembles International Phonetic Alphabet bilabial click (ʘ) and the Gothic letter hwair (𐍈).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] A similar jocular glyph (called "double-dot wide O") has been suggested as a phonetic symbol for the "nasal-ingressive velar trill", a paralinguistic impression of a snort, due to the graphic resemblance to a pig snout.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] The character was proposed for inclusion into Unicode in 2007 and incorporated as character U+A66E in Unicode version 5.1 (2008).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] The representative glyph had seven eyes and sat on the baseline.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] However, in 2021, following a tweet highlighting the character, it came to linguist Michael Everson's attention that the character in the 1429 manuscript was actually made up of ten eyes.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] After a 2022 proposal to change the character to reflect this, it was updated later that year for Unicode 15.0 to have ten eyes and to extend below the baseline.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] The incorrect form originally implemented into Unicode (2007–2022).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Broad On is used only in the Church Slavonic language.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] In its alphabet (in primers and grammar books), broad and regular shapes of О share the same position, as they are not considered different letters.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Uppercase is typically represented by broad Ѻ, and lowercase is either regular о or dual: both broad ѻ and regular о (in the same way as Greek uppercase Σ is accompanied with two lowercases σ, ς).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Phonetically, broad Ѻ ѻ is the same as regular О о.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Historically, Broad On was also used in the later Old Russian period, including documents, letters and other vernacular texts, to signal the initial position of a word or a syllable or occasionally to mark a closed vowel (developed in North Russian dialects since the 14th century).
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] It is found in birch bark manuscripts and in some other Russian texts.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Other glyphs could be used in the same functions, including Monocular O and Cyrillic Omega.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Broad On has no standard traditional name.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] The names used in literature (e.g. wide on) are shape-based or functional descriptions.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] A name from certain Russian sources, он польское, *on pol'skoye* (lit.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] "Polish O"), also points to the round shape of the letter, because Latin fonts from Poland had round "O", and the typical old Cyrillic "O" was lens-shaped and condensed.
[src:cyrillic-o-variants/cyrillic-o-variants] Now the character is often referred to by its conventional Unicode name "Round Omega".
